    text: "| THE EXPECTED MILL.\n\n| LE\n\nChicanery of Rooke and His New\n\nYork Backers.\n\nA Row Raised About the Final Stake-\nHolder.\n\nRooke Not to Appear in the Ring\nTo-Day. :\n\nHe Sends a New Proposition to Allen.\nens TRE\n\n[Special to the St. Louis Republican.]\n\nNEW YORK, June 16.—For the past two\nweeks sporting men have been eagerly look-\ning forward to the fight between Tom Allen\nand George Rooke of New York for the honor\nof the title champion of America and $3,000.\nPreliminaries for this contest were arranged\nin such a business-like manner that those who\nhad looked upon the mateh with suspicion and\ndistrust changed their minds and believed the\npugilists would fizht. On June 1 the final |\nstake-holder waa selected, Mr. Jno. Chamber-\nlain. He accopted. A few days later he was\ninformed that Joe Coburn had organized a\ngang of rufians to go ‘on to Pittsburg\nand win the fight for Rooke if he\n\n| was not able to do so himself. This plan was\nto be carried out strictly to the letter, as fol-\nlows: If the Rooke party could not secure a\nreferee in their favor they determined to win |\nthe fight on an alleged foul. If they were\ni balked in the referee business the gang from\n{ New York were to crowd in Allen’s corner\n| and when Rooke forced the fighting a cry of\nfoul was to be raised in Allen’s corner by\nRooke’s friends. Then the latter were to\nbreak down the ropes in Allen’s corner and |\nitooke’s seconds were to claim the fight\non the ground that Allen’s friends\nbroke into tke ring. The referee would then\n[ be cblized to give his decision in favor of!\nRocke, according to the rules. Backers of |\nRocke would then receive the stakes, and if\nAllen sued he could not recover. Chamber- |\nlain, however, at the eleventh hour, declined\nhaving anything to do with the affair becanse\niwo of nis friends had money mn Rooke’s\n| $1,590, and they understanding they were to i\nbe cheated out of it, claimed the money they i\nhad put in the stakes, and he refused\nto have anything to do with the aflair. |\nNo blame can be attached to Allen. He\nthought he had only to fight and win. Rooke\nwas also anxious to fizht, knowing that if he\ncould not win the Coburn gang would win\nfor him.\n\nPrize-fighting has fallen into decay, not only\namong the once reputable sporting men, but\namong the rougher element who have patron.\nized pugilists. The wretched bruisers who\nhave formed the central figures of the brutal\ngatherings found that getting a shocking drub-\nbing with the usual mutilations put money\nonly into the purses of their backers. A prize\nfight for £3,000 meant that certain well-to-do\nbrutes stood a chance of winning as much\nmore as they could extra from the savage\ncuriosity of the motley crowd by excursion\nmoney. Because there was no possibility of\nan excursion from Pittsburg is one of the prin-\ncipal reasons why Rooke’s backers would not\nagree to Harry Hill of New York for stake-\nholder. The victor in one of the latter-day\nfights found himself a beggar around the fishy\nhaunts of his patrons, while the vanquished,\nwith a face like a piece of claret jelly, thrown\nagainst the wall, was despised and left help-\nless on the scene of the contest. So\nthe pugilists wisely deserted what\nwas miscalled ‘the manly art,’’ to the swind-\nling tactics of their backers. Fights were ar-\nranged, excursions got up at five dollars\neach; no fights took place, except occasional\n“¢‘scrimmages’’ during the trip when some cit\nizen objected to being robbed by gamblers -and\nthieves, who were passed on board free in or-\nder that theymight break up the fight if wanted.\nThe principals in the meantime are purposely\narrested or take the wrong tran, or if they do\nget into the ring, they fail to agree upon a ref-\neree.\n\nTo-day the backers of the men met to\ndecide upon a final stakeholder, when it was\ndiscovered that Shaughnessy, one of Rooke’s\nbackers, had put an attachment on the stakes\nnow held by Harry Hill. Mr. Muldoon, an-\nother of Rooke’s backers, authdrized Billy\nEdwards, Allea’s representative, to notify\nAllen that when Shaughnessy withdrew his\nshare of the money ne would make up the de-\nficit to one thousand, and if Allen would agree |\nto fight Rooke for that amount, within ten\ndays, 50 miles from Pittsburg, he would post\nthat amount with Harry Hill. Rooke is here\nwaiting Allen’s reply. He would have left for\nPittsburg but his backers would not give him\n\n| money to go.\n————",
