    text: "ee ——\n\nALLEN AND ROOKE.\nArrangements Again Made for the\nFight.\n\n————\n\nThe following special telegram to the RE-\nPUBLICAN was received last night:\n\n‘‘“NEW YORK, June 28. —Sporting men here\nare again rejoicing over a fresh match being\narranged between Allen of St. Louis and\nRooke of this city. The latter, with Billy\nBorst M. Shaughennessy and many ggorting men\nwere at Harry Hill's, this atterno ll when ar\nrangements were made by them to tight within\nfifty miles of Detroit, on the 15th of July. The\nmen are to fight for fun, and the champion-\nship of America, and on them bakers are to\nwager $1,000 aside, or more at the ring,\nwhich Harry Hill is to hold and give\nto the winner. Rooke is allowed\nto select the Dbattle-ground, and will\nhave to notify Allen five days Lefore the day\nelected for the battle. Rooke has continued\ntraining since the fizzle. Upon the above\nterms there is every prospect of a fizht. Har-\nry Hill represented Allen, but Rooke trans-\n2cted his own business. The $3,000 stakes\nat the first match between Allen and Rooke\nwas returned to the parties who posted them\nto-day. Harry Hill retains $1,000 of Allen’s\nmoney to post on the coming contest.”’\n\nINTERVIEW WITH ALLEN.\n\nOn receipt of the above intelligence, one of\nthe intellectual emissaries attached to the lo-\ncal department of the REPUBLICAN was dis-\npatched to seek an interview with the muscu-\nlar celebrity whose residence among us has\nmade our city the headquarters of one of the\ncherished institutions of the country. Deen\nwithin the classic shades of “‘Tom Allen's\nFree and Easy’’ the champion himself was\nfonnd, in the centre of a collection of choice\nspirits. The reporter announced to him\nthe intelligence received irom New\nYork concerning the new  arrange-\nments for a fight between himself and George\nRooke, and asked if this were thus. Allen re-\nplied that the information was new to him;\nthat Arry ’Ill was duly authorized to act for\nhim, but had not as yet sent him word of the\nconsummation of the new arrangements. The\nREPUBLICAN could ascertain definitely by tele-\ngraphing to 'Arry. Having ample confidence\nin its New York correspondent Mr. Hill was\nnot consulted by the REPUBLICAN for confirma-\ntion or denial of his statement; and it may be\nexpected that unless some contingency at\npresent unforseen should arise Allen and\nRooke will meet and punch one another’s heads\nat the time and place hereinbefore stated.\n\nBA vs il ar Ne RE",
