    text: "—_—————\n\nRAIDS. |\n\n—— |\n\nHow the Gamesters Bear Up Under\nAdversity.\n\nThe system of raiding followed by the police\nis being persecuted with considerable vigor\njust at present. On Saturday night every\ngambling-house in the Central district was\nraided in the early part of the evening and\nninety prisoners were captured. Of these\nforty came from Pate’s. Late at night Pate’s\nand Godfrey’s houses were visited a second\ntime aad at the former plice sixty-one players\nwere bagged. The total number ef prisoners\ntaken at the gaming rooms during\nthe night was 168. In spite of\nthis showing new keno houses are\nestabliehing in various quarters. Billy Car-\nroll, who started Saturday afternoon over\nEsher’s on Fifth street, was raided like the\nothers and saw twelve of his patrons locked up.\nTom Allen had a fine game running up stairs\nover his “‘iree and easy’’ on Washington\navenue, and it is rumored that Tom Keliy con-\ntemplated inaugurating the same business in\nconnection with his place on Sixth street.\nPresent indications are that the game will be-\ncome epidemic unless a early frost or some\nother catastrophe befall it. |",
