    text: "| STILL A MYSTERY.\n\n: —_———\n\nJ\n\n| The Shooting of Frank Rush at\n\nAllen’s Saloon.\n—_——.— ————\n\n;\n\n\"| A Theory That the Stranger Fired the Shot\nin Revenge for Previous Rough Handling\n—Rush Not sc Dangerously Injured as Was\nFirst Supposed.\n\nThe police of Central District have another mys-\nterious shooting case on hand. At 1 o'clock this\nmorning Frank Rush was shot in front of Tom\nAllen's saloon at 621 Market street by an unknown\nman, who made his escape after a very deger-\nmined attempt to murder his man. The statements\nof the various parties failed to agree in important\ndetails, which are not matters of hurried im-\npression but questions of fact concerning which\nthere is no good reason for irreconcilable stories.\nFree and easy concerts are given me at Allen's\nplace. Each person in attendance is called upon to\nadd to the entertainment, which is filled out by\nregulars when the time lags. Among those\nattaches of the place 1s Frank Rush, a coal miner,\nwho lodges over the saloon. Recently, according\nto the proprietors statement, Rush has been labor-\ning about the city, spending his evenings at the\nsaloon. Last night the crowd had dwindled down,\n\n; when a stranger, who is described as5 feet 10\ninches high, dark complexion, slim buiit, smooth\n\nface, wearing a long. dirty grey overcoat,\nlow 5 pic shoes and about 25 years old,\nentered the place. The statements of the subse-\nquent occurrence, which may possibly result in a\nmurder, are as follows: Tum Allen, the proprie-\ntor, said: “I was playing cards in the concert-\nroom when this fellow came in. He said he was\nhere from Chicago on a spree and asked for a wom-\nan on Eighth street. He was so drunk he couldn't\nlight his cigar and Rush hit him a tip. He staggered\nout after falling against the es\ntition and then he fell vg the window.\nChrist Hoff, tue bartender, told Rush to go out ana\nsee that the fellow didn’t tumble in through the |\nwindow. It wasn't half a minute before we neard\nthe shots as fast as a man could fire a gun, When\nwe got outside the man was gone.\n\nRush's first statement was as follows: “I gave\nhim a light and he staggered out against\nthe door. I went out after him to brace him up. {|\nHe fe.l against the window. I grabbed him by the\nshoulder and said: ‘Logx out, old man, you'll break\nthe window.” He said: ‘Let go, d—m you,” and\npuiled out a revolver gnd began shooting. I said:\n‘Don’t shoot, I won't hurt you,” and he said: ‘I\n\n{ guess you won't.”\n\nThose who saw the man run dway say he was not\ndrunk but ran rapidly. At the saloon even all\n\n{ parties admit that possibly the man thought he was\n\nbeing robbed, a theory gi 4 shared by the\n\n| officers. Rush had one il extracted from his\n| shoulder. The second is lodged in the chest. Two\nof tue shots evidently missed the mark.\n\nFrank Rush, the wounded man, is now resting\neasy at his room over Allen's saloon. He denies\nthat he knew the man, but on reconsidering tle\nshooting, he said that\n\nIT SEEMED LESS MYSTERIOUS\n\nthan it did last night, as he did not believe the man\nwas really as drunk as he appeared to be.\nA crowd including Tom Allen, a young ||\nfellow named Spelker<and the bartender assembled\naround Rush's bed this morning and on an inter-\nchange of opinion they came to the conclusion that\nthe shooting was premeditated. On entering the\nsaloon last night the man said he was from Chicago\nand had come to this city to en-\njoy a spree. He was then. apparentiy\ndrunk, but a few minutes later sharpened a lead\npencil, putting a fine point on without once break-\ning it. This was overlooked at the time, but, in the\nlight of the new tueory, it 1s taken as a strong evi-\ndence that the man was disseinbling. He then walsked\nback to the rear of the concert rpom, in which Alien\nand a young man were playing “sven up.” On\nhis return be bought a cigar, which he put in his\npocket, relighting a stump which he had in his\nmouth. He stagzered against Rush and apparently\nonly gained the door by chance. All are agreed\nthat a very short time elapsed between the exit of\nRush, who went to see that the window was not\nbroken, and the shots. The manner in which he\nmade his escape confirms the theory that he was\nnot as drunk as he appeared to be\n\nThe statement made by ome of the habitues of the\nChampion's Rest was that the stranger resembled a\nman who was roughly handled and ejected\nfrom the place some time ago.\n\nTHE BARTENDER\nwas of the impression that he had seen the man be-\nfore in this city. The story of the previous trouble\ncould not be traced, but seems a very reasonable\nexplanation of the shooting. Rush admits that he\ntook hold of the man, ana It is possible |\nthat the revengeful stranger also believed\nthat he was being assaulted and robbed.\nRush's wound in the chest 1s not as serious as was\nsupposed. Dr. Nidelet, who made a casual exam-\nination at noon to-day, said he rr think any of\n| the vitals had been struck by the bafl.",
