    text: "KELLY'S COURAGE\n] L]\n; —— eee\n: HE STOOD UP FOUR ROUNDS AGAINST\nJACK BURKE,\nJ\nBut Got Knocked Down Nineteen Times and\n\nFell Twice—‘The Irish Lad” Fails to Get in\n\nHis Great Right-Hander and Ed Gets His\n\n8100—A Decision Withdrawn—Much Blood\n\nand More Words—Particulars of the Contest\n\nat the Casino Last Night.\n\nThe much talked of contest between Jack\nBurke, the champion of England, and Ed\n\n' Kelly of local fame, took place last night at the\n| Casino Theater in the presence of one of the\nlargest audiences the house ever held. Every\n: local sport, prominent and obscure, was on\n! hand and the even was distinguished by the\n| presence of one or two city officials and a city\nBarstoar x gig The regular programme of the\nevening was gone through, and\nat 9:45 the stage was prepared for\n| the pugilists. After some discussion\n{ Mr. Dick Roche was fixed upon as referee.\n| Mr. Al. Spink was chosen time-kceper. Pat\n| Killen and Oscar Floto seconded Burke, and |\n{ Tom ell and Tom Allen acted as seconds for\n{ Kelly. The final upshot of the affair was the\n| decision by Mr. Roche that Burke had failed to\n| Knock out Kelly in four rounds, such being the\n| proposition, and consequently, that he must\n| forfeit the $100 he had staked on his ability to\n{ do it. Burke will pay the money to-day.\nIt was past 10 o'clock when the | ris prov\nstepped upon the stage and shook hands be-\nfore starting in to work on the first\nround. They were | phonies enthusiastically.\nThe men then went at each other, sparred for\na few moments and Burke finding an opening\nlanted a terrible blow on Kelly's neck which\nPandea him on his back. He was up again but\nwas downed a second time by Burke's left, the\nround finishing with a fall-down on the part of\nKelly. The second round saw the St, Louis\nboy hammered about generally, the English\nChampion downing him three times in rapid\nsucecession.In the third round Kelly came to the\nscratch still plucky, but a little frayed at the\nedges. In this round Burke brouzht the\nblood from Kelly's nose and mouth with some\nheavy right-handers, laying him at every blow.\nHe was knocken down twice and fell once\nwithout being touched.\nBURKE CLAIMED A FOUL\nand the referee warned Kelly that if this oc-\ncurred the second time he would declare for\nBurke. In the fourth round Kelly was still in\nthe ring though ready to fail from the mere\nwind of Burke's fist. In this round Burke\nhugged him to preyenthim falling. Kelly was\nbadly battered and fell from the slightest blow\nfrom Burke and took whatever advantage he\ncould of the ten seconds allowed him to re-\nmain on the ground when he fell. These tac-\ntics rattled Burke considerably and when time\nwas up he stepped to the front and said:\n\n. ‘Gentlemen, how can I knock aman out when\nhe is on the ground all the time? Our agree-\nment was to fight with two-ounce gloves, while\nthe fight has been with four-ounce gloves. 1\ncan’t knock a man out with pillows.”\n\nAt this juncture Mr. Roche approached the\nfootlights and declared the night a draw.\nSome hot words were had all\naround and the curtain dropped,\nwhile the crowd dispersed with\nexpressions of disgust at the evening's work.\nAfter the curtain had fallen Mr. Roche’s atten-\ntion was called to the fact that his decision\nwas erroneous, as a draw could not be decided\nin the premises. Burke had either failed to\nEnock out Kelly or he had not: therefore,\nthere could have been no draw. On this ex-\nplanation Mr. Roche withdrew his former de-\ncision and merely announced, privately, the\nfact that Burke had failed to knock out Kelly\nin four rounds.\n\n‘‘“That whole business last night was ‘Tug’\nWilson and Sullivan over again,’’ said Oscar\nFloto, Burke's manager, this morning,\nto a POST-DISPATCH reporter at the\nLaclede Hotel. “I could stay with\nBurke four rounds myself like any did.\nThe first time he went down and stayed his ten\nseconds out, I knew the whole thing was fixed\nand I suid to myself that if Jack didn't get\nhis right hand in then on Kelly's\nneck, the thing could £0 on all\nnight. That's what we wanted, and\nif Jack ever got that right-hander of his in,\nKelly would won been knocked cold. How\ncould he do it though when Kelly kept run-\nning around as though he was ina walking\nmatch instead of a fist match, Burke's opinion\nof the thing was expressed in a telegram he\nsent to Davies last night, in which he merely |\nsaid: ‘It was Tug Wilson and Sullivan.\nPshaw; Kelly ought to be able to stand up |\nnineteen rounds like he did last night without\nphasing him.””’\n\nKELLY'S FRIENDS\nfeel generally jubilant over what they claim a\nvictory. Tom took his son home and fixed\nhim up in good condition. Beyond a scratch\non his arm, which he received in a fall against\nthe flies, and a little blood from his nose, Ed is\nall right.\n\n‘‘There was nojnecessity fora decision'at all’’\nsaid Tom to-day. ‘‘It wasn't a fight at all.\nThe understanding was that Ed was to stand\nup four rounds, and he did it; that settled it.’’\n\nThe contest was according to Marquis of\nQueensberry rules. During the four rounds\nwhich were fought Kelly was knocked down\nnineteen distinct times and fell down twice.\nCalculating on the ten seconds given to re-\nmain down, and he stayed it out every time,\nthis would give him 210 seconds rest\non the fioor, or a little over one\nfull round. The on the whole was\na dy. 4 funny affair. Young Kelly\nwas backed up by his father and Tom Allen,\nwho did everything to encourage him and push\nhim to the front, and the yells of SRefiv\n‘“‘Kelly!”’ ‘“Give it to him, Ed!\"\nand a score of such marks of\napprobation from the audience man-\naged to hold Ed up considerably. After the\ncontest was over, Burke claimed that the\nagreement was to fight with two-ounce gloves,\nThe fact of the matter was, that there was a\nsplit on the gloves, Burke insisting on usin\ntwo-ounce and ow on four and\nthree-quarter-ounce gloves. A compro-\nmise was then effected on four-ounce\nweapons, it being clearly understood that soft\nand not hard gloves were to be used. Many in\nthe audience held rather strong opinions as to\nthe affair, one gentleman, weit versed in ring\nrules, holding that the decision should have\nbeen rendered in Burke's favor because of the\nfoul in Sellye falling without being touched,\nthe Queensberry rule on this point Setng that\na foul loses the fight. It was thought further,\nthat Mr. Roche erred in “*warning’’ Mr. Kelly\nas the simple fact that he had fouled gave the\nfight to his opponent.\n\n. SE JACK BURKE\n\nas no particular regret that youn Kell\nom with him the four rounds, beyond what\nlittle irritation he might naturally feel. The\nfact will not derogate, in the slightest, from\nhis reputation as a pugilist as it was altogether\na negative contest. ad Kelly stood up to the\nscratch and endeavored to Rave used his ag-\ngressive and defensive tactics at the same\ntime, which really constitutes the art of\npuetion, Burke would have paralyzed him as\n\nie did Cleary in Chicago. One good thing,\n\nat all events, will come out of it and that to\n\nKelly's benefit. He learned a lesson last\n\nnight which he will never forget and which\n\ntaught him more than he over know before.\n\nAt his next encounter he will have more con-\n| fidence and pluck.",
