    text: "GET READY, ROSS!\n|\n1 AMAN WITH MONEY WHO WILL MEET THE\nCHAMPION SWORDSMAN.\nTom Allen Deposits 8200 as Forleit For a\n| Match—President Von der Ahe Will Play |\nthe Browns Against the Chicagos—IBase\nHall Budget From Newark—International\nSculling Sweepstakes—The. Wheel.\n\nDuancar C. Ross, who claims to be the cham-\npion swordsman of the world, arrived in this\ncity yesterday from Kansas City to see Festus\nJ. Wade, the Secretary of the Fair Associa-\ntion, in reference to a proposed exhibition at\nthe Kansas State Fair. During the afternoon,\nIloss strolled around town in company with\nTom Kelly and finally wound up\nat J. W. Peckington’s Victoria House on\n’ine and Seventh streets. There he was quite\nprodigal with words and issued a general\nchallenge to any man in Missouri, soldier or\ncitizen, to meet him in a mounted sword con-\ntest, at the same time remarking that he\ncared to take part in no contest for less than\n$1,000. To show that he meant business by\nthis broad <“‘detfi,’’ Ross is said to have\nposted so00 as a forfeit with Mr.\nPeckington. This morning Tom Allen called\nat the office of the PosT-DisraTcH and said\nthat he had a man, who, for the present might\nbe considered as an unknown, who would be\npleased to meet Ross in a mounted contest or\non ioot with broadswords for the sum\nOf $200 a side, or a stake of\n$1,000, ‘““My man,'’ said Mr.\nAllen, ‘is ready to meet Ross at any time Ross\nwants him to, on a day’s notice, the sooner\nthe better. To show you that I mean business\nI will now deposit $200 with the POST-DISPATCH\nto be forfeited if we fail to come to time. Mr.\nAllen put up the money.\n\nIf Duncan C. Ross means what he says\nhe will waste no time in covering\nthis deposit and arranging the match with Al-\nlen’s man. Mr. Allen says if he cares to do so\nhe can meet him to-night at Tom Kelly's\nplace and arrange the details of the match.\n\n—— | tl\nTEY CC TFTY SY S42 221\" m> a TE 2",
