    text: "IT WILL BE CALLED OFF.\n—_————\n\nTHE STAKES IN THE DALY-M'MANUS FIGHT\nTAKEN DOWN.\n\nDaly Is Determined to Drop the Affair and\nHas Quit Training—The Story of Allen’s\nInvolvement in the Fight—A Short and\nDecisive Mill—Sporting News and Notes\n—Ball Gossip.\n\n| \"OTHING short of a\n\n| miracie can now be\n\ndone to bring off the\n\nDaly-McManus fight.\n\n3 There 1s now no\n\noh. > doubt that the\n\ngon f 7, money will be turned\n\nYad \\ #1  overto the two sides\n\nIP by the stakeholder,\n\nPAE. Y! Bill Clark, and this\nS : (Wu will in all probabili-\n\n3 79% ’ 9 %e | ty be done to-mor-\n& 38 2) row. Dan Daly is\ndn SEreseg® ving at his house\n\non Walnut street, and Charley Woods, his\nfriend and trainer, has given up the train-\ning quarters at Tower Grove, and has\n| again taken up his abode In the city. Daly\nhas quit training and is fully determined upon\nthe course which he outlined in the SUNDAY\n\nPOST-DISPATCH of yesterday. Clark called at\n\nthe Daly Bros’, place of business yesterday\n\nand said there that hewould so arrange it\nthat the fight would be brought off, but this is\nhardly possible. Daly is disgusted and so are\n| his friends, and it is at their instance\nthat he has given the affair up. He\nsaid this morning: *‘After I fought with\nEddie Kelly 7 awore 1 would never fight again,\nand I meant it. McManus knew this and took\nadvantage of it by biuffing and challenging\nnie in the theaters. He oplayed his bluff and\nwas called down, and he got Tom Allen mixed\nup in it, too. Both of them were sorry after\nthey got in and then went to work to get out\nof itthe best way they could. Of course, Mc-\n\nManus says he’s willing to fight, but he\n\nEnows there’s no danger of a fight now and he\n\ncan go ahead and blow. 1 will pay no more\n\nattention to him. I'm done fighting now for-\never.\"’\n\n**If McManus agreed to ficht and started out\nto the battie ground,’” said Woods, ‘‘he\nwould be arrested on the road to the train. It\nwould be the easiest thing in the world to stop\nthe fight, and there's no use bothering with it\nany longer.\"’\n\nA very well-known man in the business is\nsaid to have stated that Allen put up the first\n$250 forfeit, and that other parties were to put\nup the balance. When the time came forthe ||\nsecond deposit the parties were not forth- ||\ncoming, and in order to save the $250 already |\nup Allen made the second deposit.\nWhen the time arrived for the\nthird deposit the parties were still absent and\nthen Allen put that up also, and so on until\nthe entire 31,000 was deposited, and Mr. Allen\nwus face to face with the situation defined by\nthe words “‘fight or forfeit.”” If he fought he\nwould lose, or was convinced that he would\n\n1 lose, and _if he forfeited he would be\njust £1,000 poorer. These were the\nconsiderations ,which, it is said, the\n\n| well known man in the business stated, in-\n\n| duced the fat and festive Thomas to stick on\ntechnicalities and this opinion seems to be =0\nunanimous among all except Tom himself\nthat there should be some truth in it.\n\nThe man who regrets most that the fight is\noff is Mr. Charlies Augustus Woods,\nwhose science anc experience had put Daly in\nfine fettle. Charley engineered Dan through\na very long mill on one occasion and he |\nwould have keenly appreciated seeing his\nman whip the stranger from Kansas City. Be-\nsides, Charley will miss the little ‘*‘chunk of\nchink,” as he calls it, which he would have\ngot if Dan won.\n\nThe training expenses of the Daly party\namounted to about $350, but Daly says the\nwork has done him that much good. He was\nat it five weeks. 4",
