    text: "TOM ALLIN.\n\n| To the Editor of the Post-Dispatch:\n\n| Andy Bowen's seconds are to be cen- |,\nsured for their failure to throw up\nthe sponge three rounds before their |.\nman was sent down and out forever by |.\n\n| George Lavigne. To - mind Bowen was |\nclearly pm: ee then. e might not have |,\nshowed outward evidence of the terrific |.\n\n| punishment administered him, but his}.\nvitality was exhausted, In these glove con- |\ntests a man may be all but out, and still }.-\n\n| show little evidence of the fact, except to |\nan experienced eve. When a pugilist reaches |\nthis stage, there is no use of prolonging the\nbattle and his seconds should surrender\nfor him. Had Bowen been fortunate\nenough to have a man behind him who |.\nunderstood his business, 1 believe he wouid\nbe =till in the land of the living. When\nBowen went down, he was no doubt com- ||\npietely exhausted. Fresh air might have |\nrelieved him, but it could not be gotten in |\none of those incleosed fighting arenas. Thou- |)\nsands of spectators are packed inside, |\nsmoking and chewing, and the atmos- |i\nphere on a warm night is polluted like |\nsewer water. Inhalings such poison in |\nhis lungs is anything but beneficial to an | ;\nunconscious man, especially after he has |;\nreceived a drubbing like Bowen got from |\ni.avigne. I am a firm believer in fighting in |,\nthe open air, and if Bowen's death puts a | ;\nquietus on legalized glove contests, the old- |.\ntime methods will ecome into vogue once |]\nmore. Bowen's death may affect the sport |.\nfor the time being, but if it does it will be |\nonly a temporary set-back. This talk about\npugilism being dead because the IL.cuis-\niana authorities are expected to legislate\nagainst it i= all rot. Fighting flourished be-\niore the New Orleans’ clubs were ever/|{,\nheard of, and it will continue to do so after |\nthey have gene out of existence.\n\n| THOMAS ALLEN,\nRetired Champion of the World.",
