    text: "HOW AN IRISHMAN\ni\nFOR UNITED STATES\ni\nre em SE LHS SR |\n: - BY BILLY MURPHY. !\nThe writer was a guest of Professor Bill Clark, the Beifast Chicken,\nSunday afternoon. It had occurred to me, that it would prove interesting\nreading St. Patrick's Day, if TI could present to the readers of The New Star\nan authentic story of how the world's ring championship came to America.\nI had never seen such an article and knew that the beloved “Belfast Chicken”!\ncould tell me. Tn fact, I believe he is the only man in the world today, who |\nis acquainted with the true story of the retrogression of the Britisay fighters!\nand the rise of Americans, :\nHere is old Bill's story, which I report as accurately as it is possible for !\nme to do. “The Chicken” talked in this manner: ’\n“That grand old institution, the prize ring, which has an ineradicable |\ncharm for all men, attained the height of its popularity in the vear 1860, when |\nthat gallant little champion, Tom Sayers, after a struggle with John Camel!\nHeenan, the American champion, which may be truly described as stupendous, |\nretired from active work, and left the old Champion Belt open for compe- |\ntition. The troubles of the prize ring then commenced. In turn the trophy |\nwas won by Sam Hurst, the giant from Stalybridge, Jem Mace, Tom King,\nJoe Wormald, Mace again, and finally, after a number of scenes not of a |\nvery creditable nature, the police made matters so hot that a number of |\nprominent pugilists determined to try their luck in America. Just prior to!\ntheir departure, however, Joe Goss. the English champion, and Tom Allen |\nsigned articles to fight for the premier honor.\n“That intended battle really put an end to the sport in England, for both |\nmen were arrested on the eve of the fight upon bench warrants, and from |\nthe activity and earnestness shown in the matter the pugilists realized that |\nit was all over with their vocation for a time.\nOFF TO AMERICA.\n“Among the foremost arrivals in the land of the Stars and Stripes were |\nJoe Wormald, O'Baldwin, Bob Prettle, Bill Ryall, Jem Mace, Joe Goss, and |\nTom Allen. Only the doings of the two last-named, however, need claim our!\npresent attention. At that time (1867) Tom Allen was at his very best, and |\nwas a splendid specimen of an athlete, fully 5 feet 10 inches, and about 164\npounds. He could hold his own in any company, and soon after his arrival in |\nAmerica he made a match with Mike McCoole, a man almost big enough to\neat him, and he was fast making mince meat of Michael when the latter's |\nfriends opened on him with ball cartridge, and stopped proceedings. At that]\ntime ring fights were conducted on very free and easy lines in America, pistols!\nand knives playing a very prominent and lively part in the proceedings, while |\nin some of the encounters the men themselves fought on the “all in\" prin-!\n¢iple, and half the battle was frequently fought with both men on the ground. |\nBARKERS AND BOWIES, |\n“With the introduction of the British brigade, however, things mended |\nsomewhat, and when, after the departure of Mace and Co. Goss and Tom\nAllen were once more matched for the championship—not of England, bear |\nin mind, but for that of the world this time-—a fairly decent display was\ngiven. The men, of course, fought under the recognized London Prize Ring |\nRules, and all would have gone well but for a gang of ruffians who had |\nbacked Goss somewhat heavily, and when the latter was seen to be getting\nthe worst of it they presented a few barkersand bowies to the notice of the !\nreferee, and that worthy was induced to give his decision in favor of the man |\nwho would in all probability have lost if the fight had been allowed to proceed. |\n~ PADDY RYAN. |\n“While the British brigade were reaping a golden harvest by fighting\n. among themselves and giving exhibitions of the noble art, there arose a young !\nIrish-American from the city of Troy. who laid claim to the title of cnampion,\nHe fought and defeated a number of local men, and challenged Joe Goss to\nfight for the championship. There was a tremendous amount of enthusiasm |\nover the event; in fact. so much was made of it that the Attorney-General]\nof Ontario, where the fight was advertised to take place, ordered out three |\ncompanies of the Third Battalion of Infantry to arrest the disturbers of the\npeace. As a consequence the meeting between the men had to be postponed, |\nand finally, after being hunted about from place to place, the men fought on\nthe border line between West Virginia and Pennsylvania, where a terrific\nencounter was put up. However, Ryan, the younger and stronger man,\neventually compelled his antagonist to give in, after fighting nearly an hour |\nand a half. |\nTHE GENESIS OF GLOVE FIGHTING.\n: “After the Goss and Ryan battle, the authorities bestirred themselves, |\nand issued a warrant for the arrest of both men, but they managed to es-\ncape to Canada, where they had to hide until the matter was settled. a\nlegal business was rather a lengthy job, and by the time it was finished and\nRyan had returned to New York he found that a new star had come to the |\nfront. This was a young Bostonian, John Lawrence Sullivan by name, bsg\nhad been creating quite a sensation by the marvelous manner in which he |\nput his opponents to sleep with the gloves. Sullivan challenged Ryan to\nfight with these weapons, but the latter replied that as he had won the cham-\nplonship from Goss by a fight with nature's weapons the Boston glove-slinge: |\nwould have to meet him under like conditions. A tremendous amount of time i\nwas wasted in discussing the terms of the meeting, but at length Sullivan had |\nto give way, and the pair signed articles to fight under London Prize Ring |\nRules for the championship of the world and $5,000 a side.\nSULLIVAN WINS THE CHAMPIONSHIP.\n“The men met at Mississippi Cityon February 7, 1882, and a truly hurri-|\ncane fight was put up. |\n“From the first round it was practically “all over,” for Ryan was help- |\nless in the hands of the sturdy Bostonian. Sullivan simply overwhelmed and |\noutpunched his plucky opponent, and eventually won the fight with ridiculous :\nease in the short time of eleven and a half minutes. And that is how the\nchampionship went to America. : {\n“Mace who had the best right to the English title had drawn with Joe |\nCoburn. Goss beat Coburn. Goss also drew with Mace. There was no ||\ndoubt whatever that Goss was esteemed the best man in Great Britain. |\n3 “England has tried many times to wrest back the championship under\nLondon Prize Ring and Marquis of Queensberry rules, but has never been able |\nto do so. {\n| “Charley Mitchell made the best attempt of all the contenders when he!\nfought Sullivan thirty-nine rounds to a draw decision on the estate of the |\nBaron Rothschilds at Chantilly, France. But the English champion ran!\naway from Sullivan all through the fight. A draw was his alm and he got it. I:\n“Even then, Sullivan was slipping back. He had been feted and dined  ;\nin England like a god. Jack Ashton and Sullivan sparred before the Prince |’\nof Wales and Sullivan met the queen at a special reception, :\n“At 24, the ring never saw the like of Sullivan,” concluded the Professor,\n“he would have beaten men like Johnson in a punch.” Hi\nERNIE. _____AAANRRERRRRNRRRm_hee_— F",
