    text: "ENE RAE SE RTE TE I Cen wt NTT, i SS SS Se TNT I EC WN SS\n\n' | TR Cr A on, SY. LR A Ta BR ATE 2 SY vy m—-\n\ny el — |\nCOUUANNCF\nE INANYINIT BS [.\n\nPr / > 3 |\n| HE entire sports world extends greetings and felicitations to\nMaxie Adelbert Baer. He is the new heavyweight boxing cham- |\n{ pion. Administering a swishing, crushing, two-fisted attack on\nPrimo Carnera, Maxie battered the “Man-Mountain” of Italy into |\n\n9 submission in New York last night.\n\n- Carnera, whom many boxing critics insisted would never lose his |!\n\na crown, believing the European giant would carry on as king until |;\n\ny age caught up with him and forced his retirement, wilted under the |.\n\n»| power of Baer’'s fists and chucked it up in the eleventh round. 5\n\nx Carnera, regarded as a bogus champion by unbiased fistic observ- |\n\n= ers, did not go down fighting with his boots on, so to speak. Reeling i\n\n1 and staggering around from the effects of Baer's blows, Primo made\n\n| a weak effort to retain his crown. He allowed Referee Art Donovan 3\n\n1 to stop the battle. Fighting champions have always gone down offer- |\n\n’ Ing the last ounce of strength in their bodies. But then, I have )\n\nalways contended that Da Beez Preem was not a fighting champion.\n\n1 He did not fool me when he retired to the field of ex-champions last\n\n>| night. |\n\n& Ld ® a {\n\nlL AER'S victory will serve as a stimulant to the boxing game that\n\n| B was on the verge of a nation-wide close-up. In the first place\n\n| Baer is a son of America. He was born at Omaha, Neb, and |,\n\n>| received many jolts and knocks in his bovhood davs. He was a 3\n\nbutcher boy, then a kid out of the loose who went sightseeing through )\n\nlife.\n\n. When Baer entered the boxing profession he donned a dinner |\n\n: jacket. He felt that a boxer could be a gentleman and a showman.\n\nHe made friends with everyone. He joined the movie colony in Cali- i\n\nfornia, spent his money at night clubs in New York, and lolled around :\n\n| the beaches of Florida. It was his desire to sit in the front row at all\n\n: times, mainly because he was going to become the world champion;\n\n| he wanted to be the idol of the people.\n\n| Baer was not going to limit his friends and acquaintenances to :\n| members of the cauliflower industry that hang around gymnasiums.\n\n| He was going to meet the folks—say howdy to them and elevate the |\n\n: profession that for the past several years had fallen into bad repute. :\n\nWhen I received the final flash last night—“Baer wins!” I wanted :\n\n\"| to grasp Maxie's right hand and say: “Great stuff, Maxie—you're\n\n>| the type we need in the sports world—especially in boxing!” ;\n\n1 And did I join the throng that cheered Baer's victory? T hopped |\n\n: aboard the “I-Told-You” band wagon for in yesterday's forecast 1 |\n\nsaid: “Baer is my choice to win—on a knockout or the decision.” b\na * &\n\n\"| Reign of Bogus Champions Is at An End. |\n| HEN Baer won from Carnera he closed the reign of bogus |\n\nWV teavyweight champions that has existed since Gene Tunney |\n\nwent into retirement. When the ex-mariner stepped out of\n\n| competition the title became vacant. Through an elimination series\nof bouts, Max Schmeling emerged on top. The German was awarded\n\n| the crown on a foul in his bout with Jack Sharkey.\n\ns Then Sharkey came up with the honors by gaining the decision |\n\n\"| over Maxie in fifteen rounds, but his conquest was tainted by Joe |\n\n| Jacobs’ famous outburst—“We've been robbed!” There were many\n\n| who agreed with Schmeling’s manager that Maxie had received a\n\n| raw deal when the decision went to Sharkey.\n\n» El ®\nHEN Sharkey and Schmeling were engaging in their series,\nW camera, the circus freak of Europe, was imported to look\nthings over in America’s pugilistic harvest. Primo weighed\n| 270 pounds, measured six feet, six and one-half inches in height and |,\n| wore No. 17 shoes. |\n| America, the sucker country for shrewd promoters, fell for Primo’s\n\n| bulk. He was paraded into rings and ballyhooed as the “man killer.”\n\n| He knocked over a flock of fistic bums and the build-up to lead him\n\nto the championship was on, :\n| Carnera made the grade officially—by knocking out Sharkey in\n\n| June \"of last year. Despite his victory over Sharkey, Carnera re- |\nmained unimpressive in the judgment of many boxing followers.\n\n| “Carnera has pasted a bunch of palookas, but what'll he |\ndo if he ever meets a boy who is inspired to charge into the big guy\nand who has no secret strings attached to his fists?” was the ques-\n\ntion that was heard frequently around the rialto.\n\n3 The answer was delivered last night— Maxie Baer, unencumbered, :\n| laughed and joked with Primo, even vawned at the Italian's clumsy |\n\n| antics in the ring and brought the heavyweight title back to Amer- |\n| ica where it belongs.\n| Good by Primo, when does the next boat sail for Italy!\n\n- J E]\nBE ii cnnsvieiie abt. Bema Bllzial aver adad' Basia 2208 |",
