    text: "Boxing Official Describes Early\nPrize Fighting in St. Louis\nmee\n\nR = 3 a\ny TRE Pe\n\n) po aa eo = £\nSy A\nhe, / *. AN iy y.\nBIA INS. ame prs ied\n= Grd. SZ EE\npSTREA L el Bo\n\nFighters of the bare fist and small glove days, when the\npresent 15-round limit was unknown, are shown here. Jake\nKilrain, left, fought a 75-round battle with John L. Sullivan,\nJuly 8, 1889, in Marion County, Mississippi. Kilrain, now 75\nyears old, is employed as a night watchman in a shipyard at\nQuincy, Mass. Center is Harry Sharpe of St. Louis, as he ap-\npeared when lightweight champion of Missouri. Sharpe, who\nwent 77 rounds to win the longest match ever fought under\nMarquis of Queensberry rules, is shown, upper right, as he\nappears today. In the lower picture Tom Allen, heavyweight\nchampion in the 80's, who died in St. Louis April 5, 1904. is\ndriving. Seated with Allen is “Denver” Ed Smith, heavy-\nweight fighter of Denver, Colo., who was training in St. Louis\nfor his fight with Joe Goddard of Australia. He knocked out\nGoddard in 18 rounds at New Orleans March 3, 1893.\nBare Fists Flew in Late 80's\n\nand Early 90's When Most\n\nBouts Were Fought to a\n\nFinish — Skin-Tight Gloves\n\nCame Later.\n\nThe following is the first of a\nseries of articles by Har: y Sharpe\nveteran St. Louis boxing official\nwhich will review the sport in St.\nLouis from bare-fist days to the\npresent.\n\nBY HARRY SHARPE.\n\nPrize-fighting in and 1ibout St\nLouis in the late 80's and the early\n80's was popula: with the sporting\nfraternity, but it was neither promi-\nnent nor profitable except In rare\ninstances. Matches ot any 1im-\nportance were slow in the making\nand. because they were all fights to\na finish, there were long periods of |\ntraining. In addition, the fighters |\nhad either to cack themselves or\nfind someone who was willing to\nrisk fortunc upon their chances\nThis was not always easy to do, and\nwhen # “backer” was found he In- |\nvariably insisted that his fighter get\nin the best possible condition before\nhe would let him fight.\n\nThere was generally considerable\nwrangling before signing the “arti-\ncles of agreement.” it being an ad- |\nage of the ring that “a match well !\nmade is half won.” Most of the ar-\ngument concerned where the men\nwould fight, when, and for how\nrruch. It was taken tor granted\nthat the fight would be to a finish\nand there was no trouble coming\nto an understanding that the fight\nwould be with small gloves, skin-\ntight gloves, or bare knuckles. These\ntights were nearly all governed by\nthe Marquis Jf Queensberry rules\n\nthere being only a few fights in the\nvicinity of St. Louis under the Lon-\ndon Prize Ring rules following the\ndefeat of Mike McCoole by Tom\nAllen in 1873.\n\nPrize-Fighting a Felony.\n\nThe fight betwz2en Allen and Mc-\nCoole had taken place cn Chouteau\nIsland (nicknamed “Bloody” Island\nby fight followers). in the river a\nshort distance above St. Louis. This\nfight so outraged the citizens of St.\nLouis that in the following Janu-\nary the Missouri Legislature passed\na statute making prize-fighting a\nfelony and even declared giving an\nexhibition of boxing in public a mis-\n¢emeanor\n\nThis probably accounts for the\nfact that there was little prize-\nfighting or boxing in St, Louis from\nthat time until about the middle\n80's. It seems to have started again\nabout the time of Tom Allen's re-\nturn to St. Louis, after having failed\nto secure a match with Join L. Sul-\nivan for the championship of the\nworld.\n\nAllen had returned © London\nEngland, following his victory over\nMcCoole and in the meantime Sul-\nlivan came into prominence. Rich-\nard K. Fox, publisher of the Police\nGazette, a publication given over to\nsporting and theatrical events, con-\nceived a violent dislike for Sullivan\nand vowed he would find a man io\npeat him\n\nFox sent for Allen and arranged\nan exhibition with Joe Goss, whom\nAllen had previously defeated. This\nexhibition took place in Madison\nSquare Garden in New York City\nand Allen made such a miserable\nsnowing that Fox dismissed the idea\nof his fighting Sullivan\nAllen Operates “Champion's Rest.”\n\nAllen came on to St. Louis in 1884\nand engaged in the saloon business\ncalling his place the “Champion's\nRest.” It was located at the north-\neast corner of Seventh and Market\nstreets and soon became a popular\nresort for followers of pugilism. At\nthe other end of the block, Sixth\nand Market streets. Tom Kelly, a\nfcrmer English middleweight. had\nhis saloon, while around the cer-\nner from Allen. at 12 North Seventh\nstreet the Daly brothers—Dan\nCharley and Johnny—were operat-\ning their resort. These places were\nthe rendezvous of fighters, and it\nwas not long after Allen and the\nDaly brothers had established them-\nselves In opposition to Kelly that\nprofessional jealousy caused a feud\nbetween th three that was not ter-\nminat i until vears afterwards w aen\ndeath settled old scores\n\nAt this time St. Louis had loca\nfighters who fought each other. b it\nseldom i engagements outside of\nSt. Louis and vicinity The return\nof Allen set the pugilistic bee buzz-\n\nOfficials Wink at Fighting.\n\nIt began with clashes between box-\nsometimes in rough-an = imble\nIN I'Ings In the DECK of the places\nM wt )t these fights were f minor\nimportance anc ior iittle mone: but\n\nAmong the best f the local fight-\ners at this time were Dan, Charley\nand Johnny Daly, Ed Kelly. “Dutch\nNeil, Harry Allen. “Dvnamite” Ha-\nley. Hugh McManus, “Rusty” Evans\nBenny Evans, Rufus Sharpe (col-\nored) Billy Zachritz, Fred Zachritz\nArtie Flint, Josh Dickson, Prof. Paul\nPitzlin, Billy McGraw and George\nFitzgerald J\n\nAnother article tomorrow will give\nadditional highlights in St Louis\npugilistic history.",
